Immunological single-cell analysis of mononuclear cord blood cells

Elena Melnik

05 07 2021

This tutorial was made as part of the course “Single-cell data analysis” from GenomicsUa (http://genomics.org.ua/2021/03/training-course-in-single-cell-biology/)

Task: To identify the contained cells from a sample of umbilical cord blood.

Introduction

Analysis of the signal of RNA and proteins. To prepare a library, you need to take a tissue sample, such as a blood sample. Further, this sample is marked with special antibodies that bind to special surface proteins. These antibodies are linked to an oligonucleotide sequence, and this sequence also has a barcode and polyA tail that is unique for each antibody. Thanks to this sequence, it is possible to identify antibodies that bind to the protein and perform reverse transcription. As a result, we get a library of expression of genes and surface proteins.

This dataset consists of 2900 mononuclear cord blood cells. Leukocytes were removed from the sample.

Quality control of removing dead cells and cells with excess nucleotide sequences from the dataset. Finding out the percentage of mitochondrial genes.

# The number of features and UMIs (nFeature_RNA and nCount_RNA) are automatically calculated for every object by Seurat.
# We calculate the percentage of mitochondrial features here and store it in object metadata as `percent.mito`.
# We use raw count data since this represents non-transformed and non-log-normalized counts
# The % of UMI mapping to MT-features is a common scRNA-seq QC metric.
mito.features <- grep(pattern = "^MT-", x = rownames(x = cbmc), value = TRUE)
percent.mito <- Matrix::colSums(x = GetAssayData(object = cbmc, slot = 'counts')[mito.features, ]) / Matrix::colSums(x = GetAssayData(object = cbmc, slot = 'counts'))

If the cells are dead, mitochondrial transcripts are released into the cytoplasm, which is why they need to be filtered. The visualization can be seen using the violin plot. The number of mitochondrial genes is about 3%, which indicates the high quality of the data set. nFeature_RNA: the number of genes nCount_RNA: the number of reads

# The [[ operator can add columns to object metadata, and is a great place to stash QC stats
cbmc[['percent.mito']] <- percent.mito
VlnPlot(object = cbmc, features = c("nFeature_RNA", "nCount_RNA", "percent.mito"), ncol = 3, pt.size = 0.01)

Building a Scatter plot of the dependence of the percentage of mitochondrial genes on the number of reads. The plot shows that most of the cells are located in one block. It can also be seen from the graph that the percentage of mitochondrial cells is below 10, which is acceptable.

# FeatureScatter is typically used to visualize feature-feature relationships, but can be used for anything 
# calculated by the object, i.e. columns in object metadata, PC scores etc.
FeatureScatter(object = cbmc, feature1 = "nCount_RNA", feature2 = "percent.mito")

Scaling the data ## Cluster and visualize cells using the usual scRNA-seq workflow, and examine for the potential presence of batch effects. The normalization method used in the antibody array ‘CLR’ is different from RNA ‘LogNormalize.’ There are significant differences between preparing an antibody library when we do less amplification and an RNA library.

#with the help of this command you can switch into the AB assay
DefaultAssay(cbmc) <- 'ab'

## Normalizing across features

DefaultAssay(cbmc) <- 'RNA'

cbmc <- NormalizeData(object = cbmc, normalization.method = "LogNormalize", scale.factor = 1e4)

Filtrating only high variance genes in cells since only these genes will help us explain the diversity of our cells and later designate the type of cells. Using the VST method and set the number of genes to be found - 2000. We also remove ribosomal genes, as they cannot help explain the diversity of cells and harm the result. To do this, we look for all genes that begin with RPL and RPS and delete them. We can see that at first, there were 2000 genes, and after the removal, it became 10 less or 1990

#FindVariable Features, remove the ribosomal genes from the variable features
cbmc <- FindVariableFeatures(cbmc, selection.method = "vst", nfeatures = 2000)
length(x = VariableFeatures(object = cbmc))#length before removal
## [1] 2000
markers.remove <- grep(pattern = "^RPL|^RPS",  x = rownames(x = cbmc), value = TRUE)#identify ribosomal genes
VariableFeatures(object = cbmc) <- VariableFeatures(object = cbmc)[!(VariableFeatures(object = cbmc)%in%markers.remove)]#remove them from the Variable Features
length(VariableFeatures(object = cbmc))#length after removal
## [1] 1990

Combining the plot1 and the new plot of the most highly variable genes into one graph. We can see on the graph the T-cells such as GZMK, GNLY, KLRB1, TRDC. These cells belong to the constant region of the T-cell receptor (TR) delta chain that participates in antigen recognition. All marked genes in the plot belong to CD8 cells. CD8 (cluster of differentiation 8) is a transmembrane glycoprotein that serves as a co-receptor for the T-cell receptor (TCR). The MS4A1 gene belongs to CD20 cells.The genes of CD20 cells can be markers of late b-cells and even persist in plasma cells. IGLC3 gene for immunoglobulin light chain constant 3. The immunoglobulin light chain is the small polypeptide subunit of an antibody (immunoglobulin). These genes were described as plasma cells. As a result, we see diversity: T-cells, B-cells, plasma cells.

# Identify the 20 most highly variable genes

DimPlot(cbmc)

Elbow plotting is a selection of only one of the 50 dimensions of the PCA. Visualization standard deviation of each PC. We can observe a large standard deviation on the graph initially, and further along the x-axis, it does not increase. As a result, we conclude that the point after which further values can be discarded due to the insignificant variety of cells should be right after the elbow. 10 dimensions will be used for further dimension reduction.

#look into the ellbow plot to determine the number of the PCs
ElbowPlot(object = cbmc, ndims = 50)

Visualizing the genes of each dimension calculated by principal component analysis using a heatmap. Generation of 20 graphs for each dimension. On the first map, 4 zones can be clearly distinguished, a clear zone for positive and negative PCs. According to the previous graph of the dependence of the standard deviation on the PCs, we should cut off all dimensions from 9 onwards. In any case, it is worth reviewing all heatmaps and deciding whether they make sense. For example, heat map 10 shows the cytokine gene CCL5 released by a large number of immune cells, which can be described as T cells. Therefore, they are also important for us in this dimensionality reduction. DASP2 is a gene involved in the Negative Feedback Regulation of T Cells that important for complexity. CD8As (Cluster of Differentiation 8a) or CD8-positive T cells that are a critical subpopulation of MHC class I-restricted T cells and are mediators of adaptive immunity. Since heatmap 10 contains genes important for complexity, we will cut off all points after it according to the elbow plotting. From the 12th heat map, we no longer see the differences between cells.

By the distance between clusters, we can say that cluster 0 is more related to cluster 3 than to cluster 2. This umap technology is more preferable than dimplot.

#what a beautiful UMAP!
DimPlot(cbmc, reduction = 'umap', label = TRUE, pt.size = 1, label.size = 8)

Since our cells are cord blood cells without leukocytes, we expect to see only immunological cells in our analysis. Paying attention to the main marker genes. Visualization of marker gene types. It is very convenient to use looping to spare time. In our case, the loop is played 5 times. For T cells of the CD3A gene, expression is observed in clusters 0, 3, 5, located close to each other. And also in some places of clusters 2 and 4. A similar situation is observed in the T cells of the CD4 gene. We see a signal from clusters 1 and 4 and from cluster 0. In the other graphs, the situation is clearer. The CD8A gene is unambiguously expressed in cluster 3, CD14 for myeloid cells is expressed for clusters 1 and 4, which are close. A B cells can be found in cluster 2. In cluster 4, CD14 is a myeloid cell marker, and CD3 is a T cell marker. Thus, it can be concluded that cluster 4 contains myeloid-T doublets.

#look into some key markers for immune cells 
DefaultAssay(cbmc) <- 'RNA'
genes_rna <- c('CD3E', 'CD4', 'CD8A', 'CD14', 'CD19')
#CD3E - for T Cells
#CD4  - for CD4 T cells
#CD8A - for CD8A t cells
#CD14 - for myeloid cells
#CD19 - for B cells

#nice way to iterate in plotting
for (i in 1:length(genes_rna)){
    print(FeaturePlot(cbmc, reduction = 'umap', features = genes_rna[i], cols = c('grey','red'), pt.size = 1, label = TRUE))
}

We are faced with a situation where we have a protein without RNA. On the graph for the CD4 gene we have a very strong signal in cluster 3, on the graph for RNA it is weaker. Removal from analysis of risobomal genes and genes of receptors that do not help to describe the identity of the cell. TCRs only describe a T cell receptor.

#look into the DE expression of each cluster
featurescbmc <- rownames(cbmc)

cbmc.markers <- FindAllMarkers(object = cbmc, only.pos = TRUE, min.pct = 0.25, logfc.threshold = 0.25, features = featurescbmc)

Displaying Average Expression on a heat map in each cluster For example, in cluster 0, T cells are most expressed. In cluster 1 - myeloid cells. 3 - B cells. 4 - CDA+ T cells. In this heat map, we do not see absolute values but only how much one cluster expresses more than another.

#look into the average heatmap
DoHeatmap(cluster.averages_cbmc, features = top10$gene)

Using a dot-plot that shows the number of genes and percentage of the expressed cells. This plot is important since we can have 1 cell that is overexpressed, and then the entire previous heat map looks more expressed in a certain area. This graph shows the size of the point. For example, we suggest gene expression at a low percentage. This means that this gene does not pass quality control.

#look into the DotPlot
top5 <- cbmc.markers %>% group_by(cluster) %>% top_n(n = 5, wt = avg_log2FC)
DotPlot(cbmc, features = unique(top5$gene), dot.scale = 8) + RotatedAxis()

We found cells in the first 4 clusters, but the previous plot in cluster 5 is not clear which cells. They are similar to T cells, but differ slightly and are a small subpopulation. Testing the CCR7 and CD45RA markers of naive T cells. They were not found in cluster 5. Taking marker genes for memory cells, negative loop response, and differential factor. It becomes clear that in cluster 5, based on the level of expression of the S100A4 gene, there are memory cells.

Renaming clusters to identified cells in metadata by looping

#assign names for your clusters:
for(i in 1:nrow(cbmc@meta.data)){
    if(cbmc@meta.data$seurat_clusters[i] == 0){
        cbmc@meta.data$cluster_names[i] <- 'CD4 T-cells'
    }
    if(cbmc@meta.data$seurat_clusters[i] == 1){
        cbmc@meta.data$cluster_names[i] <- 'Myeloid'
    }
    if(cbmc@meta.data$seurat_clusters[i] == 2){
        cbmc@meta.data$cluster_names[i] <- 'B cells'
    }
    if(cbmc@meta.data$seurat_clusters[i] == 3){
        cbmc@meta.data$cluster_names[i] <- 'CD8 T-cells'
    }
    if(cbmc@meta.data$seurat_clusters[i] == 4){
        cbmc@meta.data$cluster_names[i] <- 'Myeloid-T doublets'
    }
    if(cbmc@meta.data$seurat_clusters[i] == 5){
        cbmc@meta.data$cluster_names[i] <- 'T memory'
    }
}

Discussion

Summing up the results of the single-cell analysis, 6 types of cells were found that are contained in the cord blood in two ways: two types of T cells, B cells, myeloid cells, and myeloid-T doublets. In addition, it evaluated the types of cells that are best tracked using the RNA array and the antibody array. Qualitative and quantitative analysis has been carried out.
